Ibrahim Oyewale, Lokoja Kogi State Commissioner for Water Resources, Mr. Abdulmumuni Danga, has appealed to residents of some communities currently experiencing acute shortage of water supply in their areas to be patient as the state government is taking measures to ensure that normalcy returns. This was contained in statement issued by Danga, which was made available to journalists in Lokoja yesterday, said the water would soon return to various homes after the major repairs had been carried out. The statement said: “I want to use this medium to appeal to various communities in and around Lokoja metropolis over the non-availability of water supply. “I want to put it on record that the scarcity of water was not intentional as some are beginning to read so many meaning to it without investigating the reasons they have not be having water supply. “The non-supply of water was as a result of the damage from the major pipeline supplying water from the main source at Lokoja greater water works to the main reservoir before distribution to the populace. “It is very pertinent at this time for us to rectify it because of the large quantity of water we’re losing through the damage anytime there’s supply. “I want to appeal again that there’s no better time to do it than this dry season because of the marshy or swampy nature of the vicinity where the pipeline is situated. By God’s grace, concerted efforts are in place both day and night to finish the work as soon as possible. “I also want to use this medium to inform the general public that GYB led administration will continue to serve and place the welfare of all Kogites and other settlers above anything because we’re here because of you,” the commissioner stated. It would be recalled that the commissioner had earlier informed the residents of Lokoja and its environs would not get water for five weeks due to major repairs of pipelines to supply water to some communities.